solutions.content:
This problem illustrates that we can sometimes combine two inefficient strategies into one efficient one. Let's see how!

There are two approaches that are slow on their own but rather easy to come up with:

#### Strategy #1
* Maintain a total number of 1s in `nums1`.
* When we see a type 1 query, go through `nums1` and update every element within the request range and renew the 1-count. This is O(N).
* When we see a type 2 query, just take the 1-count * P and add it to the sum. This is O(1).

#### Strategy #2
* Maintain a sorted list of "change points."
* When we see a type 1 query, add a pair of change points, one +1 and one -1, at the start and end of the requested range. This can be done in O(log N) with a binary search tree.
* When we see a type 2 query, go through the change points with a running total of changes, and if the sum is currently odd then add the number of zeros to the sum in the previous interval instead. This is O(change list size) = O(number of type 1 queries seen so far), which can be up to O(N).

As we can see, if there are lots of type 1 queries a only a few type 2s, strategy 2 is better. And conversely if there are many type 2 queries and few type 1s, strategy 1 is better.

So why don't we combine the two? Turns out we can!

Let's say we use strategy #2. Keep using it until the list of change points reaches some threshold `T`. Then we go through `nums1` and "push the changes in," which would allow us to clear our change list!

So what's the best choice for `T`?

Well, every time we push the changes in and update `nums1`, that takes O(N) time. Also in the worst case, there are O(N) type 1 queries. This means we'll need to run the update roughly O(N / T) times, resulting in O(N * N/T) running time overall. On the other hand, every type 2 query now takes O(T) because that's the maximum size of our change list, and there are O(N) type 2 queries in the worst case.

This means we want to balance O(N * T) with O(N * N/T), so boom, set T=sqrt(N).

